knowledge_graph.title: Horchata
knowledge_graph.description: Horchata, or orxata, is a name given to various beverages, which are generally plant based, but sometimes contain milk. In Spain, it is made with soaked, ground, and sweetened tiger nuts. In some parts of the Americas, the base is jicaro, melon or sesame seeds, or white rice, along with other spices.

related_questions.question: What is a horchata made of?
related_questions.snippet: Horchata is a sweet Mexican drink made from rice. Horchata is made by blending white rice and cinnamon sticks in water and letting them soak overnight. After the rice and cinnamon are discarded, the remaining liquid is then flavored with vanilla, sugar, and ground cinnamon.

related_questions.question: What the heck is horchata?
related_questions.snippet: In general, horchata is a sweet, dairy-free beverage that is made via a process of soaking grains, nuts, or seeds overnight in water. This mixture is then drained, and sugar or other spices are added to sweeten the beverage.
related_questions.title: What Is Horchata? Refreshing With A Little History - Backyard Taco

related_questions.question: What does horchata taste like?
related_questions.snippet: Horchata flavor can vary greatly depending on the recipe, but in general, these are mild, sweet, and creamy beverages, perfumed with local spices and sweetened with natural sugars. They're meant to be refreshing, and some are more filling than others, but most accomplish a cooling and soothing effect.

related_questions.question: Is horchata good or bad for your health?
related_questions.snippet: The long list of micronutrients in horchata are important for thyroid and muscle function, and hormone and bone health. So like we said earlier, it's great to lean mostly on water for hydration, but horchata offers added nutrition that water doesn't, so it can totally be a part of a healthy diet!

buttons.subtitle: What Does Horchata Taste Like?
buttons.title: How to Make Horchata: A Simple Recipe for Perfect ... - MasterClass
buttons.snippet: What Does Horchata Taste Like? Horchata is a flavorful rice milk beverage that is sweet and creamy, with a smooth texture, and a taste that is reminiscent of rice pudding. The sweetness of horchata depends on how much sugar and vanilla are used. When nuts are added to horchata, it gives the drink a more earthy flavor.

buttons.subtitle: Who Invented Horchata
buttons.title: Horchata - Wikipedia
buttons.snippet: The drink originated in west Africa, and it is estimated that during the 11th century, it began to spread throughout Hispania (now Spain and Portugal). There are 13th-century records of an horchata-like beverage made near Valencia, where it remains a common drink.

buttons.subtitle: Origin Of Horchata
buttons.title: What Is Horchata? | Cooking School - Food Network
buttons.snippet: While Mexican-style horchata is the most commonly known variety in the US, horchata actually originated in Spain, and there are various types of horchatas throughout the Spanish-speaking world. Horchata was born in the region of Valencia in Southern Spain.
